"""
MKT Original Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 13–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-2chronicles-13-17.py

Ch 13: Abijah vs. Jeroboam — key translation: "covenant of salt" (bĕrît melaḥ, v5);
       "worthless troublemakers" (bĕnê bĕliyaʿal, v7); divine warrior victory pattern.
Ch 14: Asa's reform and the Cushite campaign — key: dāraš ("seek," theological keyword
       of Chronicles, vv2-7); Zerah the Cushite (possibly Libyan, v9); Asa's prayer (v11).
Ch 15: Azariah's prophecy — covenant reciprocity formula (v2); the keyword dāraš
       continues; "covenant to seek the LORD" (v12) echoes Deut 6:5 language.
Ch 16: Asa's decline — the great irony: Asa who sought God now fails to seek him (v12);
       "The eyes of the LORD range throughout the earth" (v9) — šûṭ vocabulary from Zech 4:10;
       šālēm lēb ("fully committed heart") — same root as Solomon's name.
Ch 17: Jehoshaphat's beginning — unprecedented teaching mission (vv7-9); the way of
       David vs. the way of Israel (vv3-4); dāraš and derek pattern continues.

Key decisions:
- dāraš rendered "seek" or "seek out" consistently across all five chapters — the
  theological keyword of Chronicles that marks faithfulness or its absence
- "covenant of salt" kept literally with explanatory note rather than paraphrased
- Numbers (army sizes, plunder) treated as hyperbolic convention, noted where relevant
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2 = {
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The regnal formula for Abijah: synchronized with the eighteenth year of Jeroboam&rsquo;s reign in Israel. The Chronicler uses the synchronized dating convention inherited from Kings (1 Kgs 15:1). The synchronism links Judah&rsquo;s faithful Davidic succession to the parallel history of the northern kingdom — two rival claims to Israel&rsquo;s identity are now in open conflict.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Abijah reigned three years; his mother was Micaiah daughter of Uriel of Gibeah. The name &ldquo;Micaiah&rdquo; here differs from &ldquo;Maacah daughter of Abishalom&rdquo; in 1 Kgs 15:2 — either a divergent tradition, a throne name, or the same woman known by two names. The Chronicler does not harmonize but preserves his source. MKT renders the name as given in 2 Chronicles rather than importing 1 Kings&rsquo; reading.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The army sizes — 400,000 for Abijah, 800,000 for Jeroboam — are the largest in a context where Chronicles elsewhere uses similarly large numbers (cf. 1 Chr 21:5: David&rsquo;s census counts 1.1 million fighting men). Ancient Near Eastern military narratives routinely employed hyperbolic numbers to convey magnitude rather than precise census data. MKT renders the Hebrew numbers straightforwardly without editorial reduction; the rhetorical convention is part of the Chronicler&rsquo;s literary register.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Abijah takes position on Mount Zemaraim and delivers a speech — a characteristic Chronicler technique of embedding theological interpretation in battle speeches (cf. Abner&rsquo;s speech in 2 Sam 2:26-27; Hezekiah&rsquo;s in 2 Chr 32:7-8). The speech that follows (vv5-12) is unique to Chronicles and has no parallel in Kings — it is the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological digest of what was at stake in the battle.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The phrase <em>bĕrît melaḥ</em> — &ldquo;covenant of salt&rdquo; — is a key term: salt was used in ancient covenant ceremonies to signify permanence and inviolability (Num 18:19 uses it for the Aaronic priesthood&rsquo;s portion; Lev 2:13 requires salt with every grain offering). The &ldquo;salt covenant&rdquo; is permanent because salt preserves — what is salted does not decay. MKT renders it &ldquo;covenant of salt&rdquo; to preserve the concrete image rather than paraphrasing as &ldquo;permanent covenant,&rdquo; keeping the ancient covenantal idiom visible.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jeroboam is described as &ldquo;a servant of Solomon son of David who rose up and rebelled against his master.&rdquo; The word <em>ʿeḇed</em> (servant/official) underlines the political subordination that makes Jeroboam&rsquo;s rebellion a breach of covenant loyalty — <em>mārad</em> (rebel/revolt) is the technical term for covenant treason in the ancient Near East (cf. Josh 22:16; 2 Kgs 1:1; Neh 2:19). The Chronicler frames schism not as legitimate political division but as covenant rebellion.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>Bĕnê bĕliyaʿal</em> — &ldquo;sons of Belial&rdquo; or &ldquo;worthless troublemakers&rdquo; — is a fixed idiom meaning men without worth, loyalty, or social standing (cf. Judg 19:22; 1 Sam 2:12; 10:27). MKT renders this &ldquo;worthless troublemakers&rdquo; to capture both the social contempt and the moral judgment. Rehoboam is described as &ldquo;young and inexperienced&rdquo; (<em>naʿar wĕrakh lēb</em> — &ldquo;a young man and tender of heart/inexperienced&rdquo;) — the same kind of language used of Solomon at his accession (1 Chr 22:5; 29:1).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abijah identifies the golden calves as Jeroboam&rsquo;s &ldquo;gods&rdquo; — <em>ʾĕlōhîm</em> — using the exact language Jeroboam himself used at their installation (1 Kgs 12:28: &ldquo;Here are your gods, Israel&rdquo;). The polemical force is deliberate: what Jeroboam presented as representation of YHWH, Abijah names as rival deities. The rhetorical question &ldquo;You are a great crowd&rdquo; acknowledges their numerical superiority while dismissing it as irrelevant given their apostasy.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The rhetorical question about expelling the Aaronic priests is a pointed legal argument: Jeroboam installed non-Levitical priests who consecrated themselves through offering animals (1 Kgs 12:31; 13:33). The phrase &ldquo;anyone who brings a young bull and seven rams for consecration&rdquo; parodies the ordination offering — comparing it unfavorably to the divinely specified Aaronic consecration. The term &ldquo;so he could become a priest of what are not gods&rdquo; is cutting: <em>lōʾ ʾĕlōhîm</em> (not gods) echoes Deut 32:17 and 21.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The declaration &ldquo;But we have the LORD as our God, and we have not abandoned him&rdquo; uses the verb <em>ʿāzaḇ</em> (abandon/forsake) — the antonym of <em>dāraš</em> (seek). In Chronicles&rsquo; theological vocabulary, every king either &ldquo;seeks&rdquo; YHWH or &ldquo;abandons&rdquo; him; these two verbs frame the entire theological assessment of the monarchy. The priests of Aaron are named as the validation of legitimate worship — the Aaronic line is the divinely authorized access point.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The triple enumeration of daily cultic acts — burnt offerings, fragrant incense, and the showbread — names the three primary daily services of the tabernacle/temple (Exod 27:20-21; 30:7-8; 25:30). The phrase &ldquo;the service of the LORD our God&rdquo; (<em>mišmeret YHWH ʾĕlōhênû</em>) is the technical term for priestly watch-duty. The Chronicler presents the regular cultus as the concrete expression of seeking YHWH — faithful liturgy is not mere ritual but covenantal fidelity made visible.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;God is with us at our head&rdquo; (<em>wĕhāʾĕlōhîm ʿimmānû bĕrōʾš</em>) — the divine warrior leading from the front. The priests&rsquo; trumpets (<em>ḥăṣōṣĕrōt</em>) were the cultic instruments ordained for battle by the Priestly tradition (Num 10:9: &ldquo;when you go to war...blow an alarm with the trumpets&rdquo;). The battle is framed as a cult-act as much as a military engagement. &ldquo;Do not fight against the LORD, the God of your ancestors&rdquo; — the warning that resistance to Judah is resistance to YHWH himself.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The tactical backstory is introduced as an aside: Jeroboam had already deployed an ambush from the rear. The structural irony is deliberate — Judah is encircled, humanly speaking, before the battle prayer. The crisis is real; the victory that follows is therefore unambiguous divine intervention, not military strategy.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The battle response is a liturgical act: they &ldquo;cried out to the LORD&rdquo; (<em>zaʿăqû laYHWH</em>) and the priests blew the trumpets. The verb <em>zaʿaq</em> (cry out/call for help) is the word used for Israel&rsquo;s cry in Egypt (Exod 2:23; 14:10) — the cry of the helpless to their covenant God. The Chronicler presents the battle of Zemaraim as a new Exodus moment: surrounded, outnumbered, crying to YHWH, and rescued by divine intervention.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;As they shouted (<em>hēriʿû</em>), God struck Jeroboam.&rdquo; The battle cry (<em>tĕrûʿâ</em>) is simultaneously a military and cultic act — the same word used for the Jericho shout (Josh 6:20) and the trumpet blast that inaugurates the new year (Lev 23:24). The moment of Israel&rsquo;s battle cry was precisely the moment of divine action. MKT preserves the verb &ldquo;raised a battle cry&rdquo; rather than paraphrasing to capture this dual cultic-military resonance.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;God gave them into Judah&rsquo;s power.&rdquo; The divine passive of military victory (<em>nātan bĕyad</em> — gave into the hand of) is the standard theological formula for YHWH&rsquo;s decisive military action (cf. Deut 7:2; Josh 2:24; Judg 1:2). Human armies fight, but the outcome is God&rsquo;s to give or withhold. The Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent use of this formula frames every battle as a theological verdict, not merely a military result.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Five hundred thousand &ldquo;chosen men&rdquo; (<em>bāḥûr</em>) of Israel fell — half of Jeroboam&rsquo;s 800,000 army. The number continues the hyperbolic register of the narrative; its purpose is to convey total, devastating, divinely-executed defeat. The adjective <em>bāḥûr</em> (chosen/selected — picked troops) makes the defeat even more emphatic: not conscript levies but Israel&rsquo;s elite forces are destroyed.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theological interpretation of the battle outcome: Israel was &ldquo;humbled&rdquo; (<em>kānôaʿ</em>) and Judah prevailed because they &ldquo;relied on&rdquo; (<em>šāʿan</em>) YHWH. The verb <em>šāʿan</em> (lean on/rely on) becomes the key diagnostic for Asa&rsquo;s faithfulness in ch 14 and unfaithfulness in ch 16. MKT uses &ldquo;relied on&rdquo; consistently for <em>šāʿan</em> to keep this theological tracking visible across the narrative.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Abijah pursues and captures three cities: Bethel, Jeshanah, and Ephrain. The capture of Bethel is particularly significant — Bethel was one of the two golden-calf shrines (1 Kgs 12:29). Its temporary capture by Judah underlines the theological point: the city of the false gods fell to the army that &ldquo;relied on the LORD.&rdquo; The capture is not maintained; Bethel reverts to Israel&rsquo;s control, but the moment is noted.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Jeroboam never recovered his strength (<em>koḥ</em>) during Abijah&rsquo;s lifetime. The LORD struck him, and he died.&rdquo; The verb &ldquo;struck&rdquo; (<em>nāgap</em>) is the same verb used for YHWH&rsquo;s plague-action in Exodus (Exod 12:23, 27). Jeroboam&rsquo;s death is framed as divine judgment — the culmination of his rebellion against the Davidic covenant. 1 Kings 14:20 notes only that he died; 2 Chronicles explicitly attributes it to a divine blow, consistent with the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological interpretation of royal history.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abijah&rsquo;s strength grows: fourteen wives, twenty-two sons, sixteen daughters. Large family is consistently a sign of divine blessing in the patriarchal and royal narratives (Gen 22:17; 1 Chr 25:4-5 — Heman&rsquo;s 14 sons given &ldquo;according to God&rsquo;s word&rdquo;). The detail provides a narrative contrast to Jeroboam&rsquo;s enfeebled end — the one who relied on God flourishes; the one who rebelled dwindles.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The citation to &ldquo;the chronicle of the prophet Iddo&rdquo; (<em>midrāš hannāḇîʾ ʿiddô</em>) — the word <em>midrāš</em> here means a narrative composition or interpretation, not the later rabbinic genre. This is one of several prophetic source citations unique to Chronicles (cf. 2 Chr 9:29; 12:15; 20:34), reflecting the Chronicler&rsquo;s access to and use of prophetic court records that have not survived independently.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;The land enjoyed ten years of rest (<em>šāqaṭ</em>) during his reign.&rdquo; The verb <em>šāqaṭ</em> (be quiet/undisturbed/at rest) is the term used for the covenant rest of the land (cf. Josh 11:23; 14:15; Judg 3:11). It is distinct from the political-strategic peace and carries connotations of YHWH&rsquo;s active protection — the land rests because God stands guard. MKT renders it &ldquo;rest&rdquo; rather than &ldquo;peace&rdquo; to maintain this theological resonance.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The formulaic evaluation: &ldquo;Asa did what was good and right (<em>haṭṭôḇ wĕhayyāšār</em>) in the sight of the LORD his God.&rdquo; This double-virtue formula — <em>ṭôḇ</em> (good) and <em>yāšār</em> (right/straight/upright) — is the standard Chronicler commendation (cf. 2 Chr 31:20: Hezekiah; Deut 12:25, 28 for the underlying standard). Both terms have covenantal weight: <em>yāšār</em> is the conduct that &ldquo;fits the straight path,&rdquo; the path YHWH himself walks.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The reform items: foreign altars (<em>mizbĕḥôt hannēkār</em>), high places (<em>bāmôt</em>), sacred pillars (<em>maṣṣēḇôt</em>), Asherah poles (<em>ʾăšērîm</em>). This is the standard Deuteronomic list of forbidden cult objects (Deut 7:5; 12:3). The Chronicler uses the full Deuteronomic vocabulary of cult purge without abbreviation — he is presenting Asa as the archetype of Deuteronomic kingship, the king who implements Moses&rsquo;s commands.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Asa &ldquo;commanded&rdquo; (<em>wayyōʾmer</em> — literally &ldquo;said to,&rdquo; used in the sense of a royal command) the people to seek (<em>lidrōš</em>) YHWH and to observe (<em>laʿăśôt</em>) the law and commandments. The verb <em>dāraš</em> appears here for the first time in Asa&rsquo;s narrative as the defining action of his reign. The Chronicler structures Asa&rsquo;s narrative as a sustained meditation on what it means to &ldquo;seek&rdquo; or &ldquo;not seek&rdquo; YHWH (dāraš appears in 14:4, 7; 15:2, 4, 12, 13, 15; 16:12 — the whole arc of Asa&rsquo;s reign).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Asa removes high places and incense altars from every town in Judah — the country-wide scope distinguishes his reform from Abijah&rsquo;s, which was primarily about legitimate cult maintenance. The phrase &ldquo;incense altars&rdquo; (<em>ḥammānîm</em>) occurs in Lev 26:30; Isa 17:8; 27:9; Ezek 6:4, 6 — always in condemnation. The result: &ldquo;the kingdom was at peace under him&rdquo; — <em>šāqaṭ</em> again, connecting reform and rest as cause and effect.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;He built fortified cities because the LORD gave him rest (<em>nûaḥ lô</em>)&rdquo; — a different word for rest here: <em>nāḥaḥ</em> (give rest to) rather than <em>šāqaṭ</em>. The Chronicler uses two related but distinct rest-terms: <em>šāqaṭ</em> for the state of rest the land enjoys; <em>nûaḥ</em> for the rest that YHWH actively gives. The building program during the rest period is characteristic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s understanding that covenant faithfulness creates the conditions for constructive enterprise (cf. Solomon&rsquo;s building during rest, 2 Chr 8:3-6).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s speech to Judah contains the confession &ldquo;The land is still ours because we have sought (<em>dāraštānû</em>) the LORD our God. We sought him and he has given us rest on every side.&rdquo; The causal logic — seeking God → divine gift of rest — is the theological axiom of Chronicles. The land belongs to those who seek its true owner; rest is not achieved militarily but received as a covenant gift. The doubled <em>dāraš</em> in this verse emphasizes the point.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The army muster: 300,000 from Judah (large shield and spear) plus 280,000 from Benjamin (bow and small shield) = 580,000 total. The tribal distribution — Judah with the heavy-infantry weapons, Benjamin with archery — reflects the traditional military specializations in the Hebrew Bible (cf. Judg 20:16 for Benjaminite archery; 2 Chr 17:17 for similar numbers in Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s reign).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Zerah the Cushite with a million men and 300 chariots. &ldquo;Zerah the Cushite&rdquo; is not mentioned in Kings and may be Osorkon I of Egypt (a Libyan pharaoh, c. 924-889 BCE, since &ldquo;Cush&rdquo; sometimes refers to Libya/Nubia in this period) or a separate Cushite commander acting independently. The &ldquo;million&rdquo; (<em>ʾeleph</em> could mean either &ldquo;a thousand units&rdquo; or literally one million) continues the hyperbolic military register. The key point is the vast disproportion — Judah&rsquo;s 580,000 face a force described as overwhelming.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The battle takes place in the Valley of Zephathah near Mareshah (in the Shephelah, southwest Judah). Mareshah was a significant border city (cf. Mic 1:15) near the main route from the coastal plain into the hill country. The geographical setting is historically plausible for a Cushite/Egyptian incursion from the south and west.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s prayer is a model of the genre: &ldquo;LORD, there is no one like you to help the powerless (<em>ʾên ʿimmĕkā liʿzôr bên rab lĕʾên kōaḥ</em> — literally &lsquo;there is nothing with you to help between the many and the one without strength&rsquo;) against the mighty.&rdquo; The logic: YHWH is distinguished precisely by his ability to give victory to the weak; the disproportion of forces is not an impediment but a demonstration-opportunity. &ldquo;We rely on you (<em>šāʿannû ʿāleykā</em>) and have come against this vast army in your name&rdquo; — the verb <em>šāʿan</em> (rely/lean on) that will mark the whole Asa narrative.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD struck down (<em>wayyiggōp̄</em>) the Cushites.&rdquo; The verb <em>nāgap̄</em> (strike/plague) is the term used for YHWH&rsquo;s decisive military action — the same verb used for the death of Jeroboam (13:20) and the Exodus plagues. The Cushites &ldquo;fled&rdquo; (<em>wayyānūsû</em>) — flight before YHWH&rsquo;s army is the standard description of divine-warrior victory (cf. Exod 14:27; Josh 10:11).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The pursuit extends all the way to Gerar — deep into Philistine territory, south of Gaza. The description &ldquo;none could survive, for they were shattered before the LORD and his army&rdquo; uses the phrase &ldquo;shattered&rdquo; (<em>nišbĕrû</em>) and the divine passive &ldquo;before the LORD.&rdquo; The plunder is described as &ldquo;enormous&rdquo; (<em>rabbâ mĕʾōd</em>) — very great, continuing the scale-language of the whole campaign.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The surrounding towns are struck with the &ldquo;terror of the LORD&rdquo; (<em>paḥad YHWH</em>) — a theological term for the overwhelming fear that precedes YHWH&rsquo;s advance (cf. Exod 15:16; Deut 2:25; 11:25). This is not merely the psychological effect of military defeat but a specific divine disposition toward enemies of his covenant people. The towns fall not because of Judah&rsquo;s military force but because of YHWH&rsquo;s advance-terror.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The pastoralists&rsquo; camps (<em>ōhĕlê miqneh</em> — &ldquo;tents of livestock&rdquo;) are raided and large numbers of sheep and camels taken. The return to Jerusalem concludes the campaign. The Chronicler carefully notes that the army returns to Jerusalem — the center of the covenant community&rsquo;s life — not to Asa&rsquo;s palace. The victory is a covenant victory that properly ends in the covenant city.</p>"
  },
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>The Spirit of God &ldquo;came upon&rdquo; (<em>hāytâ ʿal</em>) Azariah son of Oded — the standard formula for prophetic inspiration in Chronicles and the Former Prophets (Judg 3:10; 6:34; 11:29; 1 Sam 10:6). The Spirit is not earned or routine; it seizes the prophet to deliver a specific message at a specific moment. Azariah is otherwise unknown — a sign that the Chronicler preserved prophetic records from multiple sources.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The covenant reciprocity formula: &ldquo;the LORD is with you as long as you are with him. Seek him (<em>tidĕrĕšûhû</em>) and he will let you find him (<em>yimmāṣēʾ lākem</em>); but if you abandon him (<em>tĕʿazĕḇûhû</em>), he will abandon you (<em>yaʿazkōm</em>).&rdquo; The symmetry is exact and deliberate: the same verb (<em>ʿāzaḇ</em>) applies to both directions of abandonment. This formula governs the entire Deuteronomistic theology of the monarchy and is directly cited by Solomon in 1 Chr 28:9. MKT preserves the symmetry with parallel syntax.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The historical retrospect: &ldquo;For many years Israel had no true God (<em>ʾĕlōhê ʾĕmet</em>), no teaching priest (<em>kōhēn môreh</em>), and no law (<em>tôrâ</em>).&rdquo; The phrase <em>ʾĕlōhê ʾĕmet</em> — &ldquo;God of truth/faithfulness&rdquo; — is a quality of YHWH himself (Jer 10:10); &ldquo;no true God&rdquo; means YHWH was not effectively present or sought. A &ldquo;teaching priest&rdquo; (<em>kōhēn môreh</em>) is the priest in his instructional/Torah-mediating role (cf. Deut 17:11; 33:10; Mal 2:6-7). The three absences — God, priest, law — identify the minimal requirements for covenant community existence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;But when in their distress (<em>bĕṣar lāhem</em>) they turned to (<em>wayyāšūḇû</em>) the LORD... and sought him (<em>wĕyidĕrĕšūhû</em>), he let them find him.&rdquo; The pattern of distress → return → seeking → finding appears throughout the Psalms (Ps 22:5; 107:6, 13, 19, 28) and the Former Prophets (Judg 3:9, 15; 1 Sam 12:10). The word <em>šûḇ</em> (return/repent) combined with <em>dāraš</em> (seek) constitutes the full idiom of covenant restoration.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;In those times it was dangerous to travel, for great turmoil (<em>mĕhûmōt gĕdōlôt</em>) troubled everyone in every land.&rdquo; The noun <em>mĕhûmâ</em> (panic/tumult/confusion) is elsewhere used for YHWH&rsquo;s own judgment-instrument (Deut 7:23; 1 Sam 5:9, 11; 14:20; 2 Chr 20:22-23). The historical chaos described is presented as YHWH-sent adversity — the negative of the &ldquo;terror of the LORD&rdquo; theme but with the same divine origin.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Nation fought nation and city attacked city, for God sent every kind of adversity (<em>kî ʾĕlōhîm hĕhāmām bĕkol ṣārâ</em>).&rdquo; The verb <em>hûm</em> (disturb/throw into confusion) has God as its explicit subject — this is theological history, not sociological analysis. The universal conflict is YHWH&rsquo;s covenant curse for abandonment (cf. Deut 28:20: &ldquo;the LORD will send on you curses, confusion, and frustration&rdquo;).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Be strong (<em>ḥizqû</em>) and do not give up (<em>ʾal yirpû yĕdêkem</em> — &lsquo;do not let your hands fall slack&rsquo;), for your work (<em>mĕlakōm</em>) will be rewarded.&rdquo; The command <em>ḥāzaq</em> (be strong) is the Mosaic-Davidic commissioning formula (Deut 31:6-7; Josh 1:6-9; 1 Chr 22:13; 28:20). &ldquo;Your hands will not be slack&rdquo; uses a idiom for discouragement that appears in Isa 35:3; Jer 38:4; Zeph 3:16. The word &ldquo;rewarded&rdquo; (<em>śākār</em>) may also be translated &ldquo;wage&rdquo; — their labor of faithfulness will not go unpaid.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Asa responds to Azariah&rsquo;s prophecy by removing &ldquo;the detestable idols (<em>šiqqûṣîm</em>) from all of Judah and Benjamin and from the towns he had captured in the hill country of Ephraim.&rdquo; The noun <em>šiqqûṣ</em> (detestable/abominable thing) is a polemical term for foreign cult objects (cf. Deut 29:17; 1 Kgs 11:5, 7; 2 Kgs 23:13). The extent of the reform is enlarged from the earlier account (14:3-5): now it reaches into captured Ephraimite territory as well.</p>",
    "9": "<p>People &ldquo;defected from Israel to Asa when they saw that the LORD his God was with him.&rdquo; The verb <em>nāpal ʿal</em> (fall upon/defect to) is the term for crossing over to an enemy in a military context (cf. 2 Sam 20:21; Jer 21:9). The movement of northern Israelites southward to worship YHWH at Jerusalem is the Chronicler&rsquo;s recurring theme of the faithful remnant in Israel rejecting Jeroboam&rsquo;s cult and returning to the Davidic sanctuary.</p>",
    "10": "<p>They assembled in Jerusalem in the third month of the fifteenth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign. The third month — <em>Sivan</em> — is when Pentecost (Weeks/Shavuot) falls (Exod 19:1 — Israel arrived at Sinai in the third month). Whether intentional or not, the assembly timing echoes the covenant gathering at Sinai, and the covenant they are about to make (vv12-13) is a Sinai-covenant renewal.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The sacrifices from the plunder: 700 cattle and 7,000 sheep. The numbers follow the round × 10 pattern of sacrificial lists (cf. Num 29; 2 Chr 7:5: Solomon&rsquo;s 22,000 cattle). The plunder from the Cushite campaign is consecrated — offered back to YHWH from whom the victory came. This is the theology of dedication: what God gives in victory belongs to him (cf. Josh 6:19 — Jericho plunder devoted to YHWH).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;They entered into a covenant (<em>bĕrît</em>) to seek (<em>lidrōš</em>) the LORD, the God of their ancestors, with all their heart (<em>bĕkol lĕḇāḇām</em>) and soul (<em>ûḇĕkol napšām</em>).&rdquo; The phrasing directly echoes the Shema and Deuteronomy&rsquo;s great commandment (Deut 6:5; 10:12; 30:6). A covenant to seek YHWH with the whole heart and soul is the formal renewal of the central Mosaic obligation. <em>Dāraš</em> (seek) is written into the covenant document itself — seeking is not incidental but constitutive of covenant existence.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Anyone who refused to seek the LORD (<em>lōʾ yidrōš laYHWH</em>) was to be put to death, whether young or old, man or woman.&rdquo; The capital sanction echoes the Deuteronomic laws for apostasy and idolatry (Deut 13:6-15; 17:12). The inclusion of &ldquo;young or old, man or woman&rdquo; underlines the universal scope — the covenant obligation falls on every member of the community without exception. This is not a royal decree but a covenant reaffirmation of Mosaic law already in force.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;They swore their oath (<em>wayyiššāĕʾû baYHWH</em>) to the LORD with a loud voice, with shouting, and with trumpets and horns.&rdquo; The verb <em>šābaʿ</em> is a niphal of &ldquo;seven&rdquo; (<em>šeḇaʿ</em>) — to oath is &ldquo;to seven oneself,&rdquo; invoking completeness/fullness in self-binding. The accompanying instruments — shouting, trumpets (<em>ḥăṣōṣĕrôt</em>), and šôpārot (rams&rsquo; horns) — identify the oath-taking as a public cultic-legal act, not merely a private decision. The combination of voice, percussion, and wind instruments is the liturgical maximum.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;All Judah rejoiced (<em>wayyiśmĕḥû... kol Yĕhûdâ</em>) over the oath, for they swore it wholeheartedly (<em>bĕkol lĕḇāḇām</em>) and sought him eagerly, and he was found by them.&rdquo; The reciprocal structure of seeking and finding concludes here: they sought wholeheartedly, and he was found (<em>wayyimmāṣēʾ lāhem</em> — niphal passive: &ldquo;he let himself be found by them&rdquo;). This is the theological climax of the chapter — divine availability is the covenant promise, and seeking it wholeheartedly is the covenant obligation. &ldquo;The LORD gave them rest on every side&rdquo; — <em>šāqaṭ</em> again: covenant rest is the consequence of faithful seeking.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Asa removes his grandmother Maacah from the position of queen mother (<em>gĕbîrâ</em>) because she made a &ldquo;repulsive image&rdquo; (<em>mipleṣet</em>) for Asherah. The office of queen mother was a formal court position in the Judahite monarchy (1 Kgs 2:19; 15:13). The noun <em>mipleṣet</em> (horror/abomination — something that causes shuddering) is unique in this form; its root suggests something that makes one tremble with revulsion. Asa burns it in the Kidron Valley — the same location where Josiah later burns cult objects (2 Kgs 23:4-12).</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;The high places were not eliminated from Israel. Yet Asa&rsquo;s heart remained fully devoted (<em>šālēm</em>) throughout his life.&rdquo; This is the standard Chronicler partial-credit formula — acknowledging incomplete reform while affirming the king&rsquo;s personal covenant integrity. The word <em>šālēm</em> (whole/complete/devoted) is the root of Solomon&rsquo;s name and the word <em>šālôm</em> (peace) — a fully devoted heart is one without internal division, wholly oriented toward YHWH.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Asa brings into the house of God &ldquo;the sacred offerings of his father and his own dedicated gifts.&rdquo; The term &ldquo;dedicated gifts&rdquo; (<em>qŏdāšîm</em>) refers to objects formally consecrated to YHWH — precious metals and temple vessels. The combination of his father&rsquo;s gifts and his own underlines continuity: the covenant faithfulness of each generation builds on and preserves what previous generations offered. The temple treasury is a multi-generational covenant deposit.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;There was no war until the thirty-fifth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign.&rdquo; The long peace is itself a covenant blessing — thirty-four years without war is extraordinary in the context of the Levant. The verse sets up the contrast: Asa&rsquo;s faithfulness produces a three-decade peace; his failure in ch 16 disrupts that peace permanently. The verse functions as a structural fulcrum — everything before it in Asa&rsquo;s reign is covenant faithfulness; everything after ch 16 is covenant failure.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The narrative turns: Baasha king of Israel fortifies Ramah to blockade Judah. Ramah (modern er-Ram, about 8 km north of Jerusalem) controlled the main north-south road — its fortification was a strategic stranglehold. The thirty-sixth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign represents a sharp reversal from the thirty-fourth year of peace in 15:19. The Chronicler&rsquo;s chronology here is discussed: some scholars note tension with 1 Kgs 15:16-17, 33 (Baasha died in Asa&rsquo;s 26th year), possibly indicating a different counting convention or a scribal error in transmission.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Asa takes silver and gold from the LORD&rsquo;s house and the royal palace to bribe Ben-hadad of Syria. The act is significant: he uses the sacred treasury of the temple — the same treasury his father Jehoshaphat and he himself had filled with dedicated gifts (15:18) — as political currency. This is the first sign of Asa&rsquo;s compromise. In ch 14, he relied (<em>šāʿan</em>) on the LORD; now he deploys the LORD&rsquo;s own resources to secure human alliance.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The treaty request uses the language of existing relationship: &ldquo;as between our fathers.&rdquo; Asa acknowledges a prior treaty between Judah and Syria, now asking Ben-hadad to break his alliance with Israel in favour of Judah. The political logic is sound — divide the enemy&rsquo;s alliances. The theological problem, identified by Hanani in v7-9, is precisely that this human strategy replaces trust in YHWH.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ben-hadad complies: his commanders capture Ijon, Dan, Abel-maim, and Naphtali&rsquo;s store cities. The list of captured cities spans northern Galilee — maximally disruptive to Israel&rsquo;s northern flank. Baasha&rsquo;s building project at Ramah collapses. From a purely strategic perspective, the policy worked. The Chronicler does not dispute its immediate effectiveness; his critique (through Hanani, vv7-9) is theological, not tactical.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Baasha stops fortifying Ramah and abandons the project. The immediate strategic objective is achieved — Judah&rsquo;s northern border is relieved. Asa has secured what he wanted through diplomatic and financial means. The narrative pause here is deliberate: the successful outcome makes Hanani&rsquo;s rebuke in v7 even sharper — what appeared to be wise policy is judged a failure of faith.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Asa mobilizes all Judah to haul away Ramah&rsquo;s building materials and uses them to fortify Geba and Mizpah. Recycling the enemy&rsquo;s fortification materials for your own defenses is a practical military measure. But again — the material gains are not disputed; what is missing from this account is any mention of seeking YHWH, any prayer, any prophetic consultation. The absence of <em>dāraš</em> is deafening.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Hanani the seer&rsquo;s rebuke is precise: &ldquo;Because you relied on (<em>nišʿantā</em>) the king of Syria and not on (<em>lōʾ nišʿantā</em> ʿal) the LORD your God, the Syrian army escaped your grasp.&rdquo; The exact same verb <em>šāʿan</em> (rely/lean on) that marked Asa&rsquo;s faithfulness in 14:11 now marks his failure. The contrast is structural: in ch 14 he relied on YHWH against overwhelming odds; in ch 16 he relies on Syria&rsquo;s army instead. The argument continues in v8: you had an even bigger enemy (the Cushites) and won because you trusted YHWH — why not trust him now?</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Remember the Cushites and Libyans — weren&rsquo;t they a massive force with great numbers of chariots and cavalry?&rdquo; Hanani explicitly invokes the Cushite victory of ch 14 as the precedent that Asa has forgotten. The &ldquo;Libyans&rdquo; (<em>Lûḇîm</em>) are mentioned here (not in ch 14) as part of the same force, presumably included as allies of the Cushite/Egyptian army. The rhetorical power: Asa&rsquo;s greatest triumph is now the standard against which his failure is measured.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theological axiom: &ldquo;The eyes of the LORD range throughout the earth (<em>šôṭĕṭôt bĕkol hāʾāreṣ</em>) to strengthen those whose hearts are fully committed to him.&rdquo; The verb <em>šûṭ</em> (range/rove/scan) is the same verb used in Zechariah 4:10 for the eyes of YHWH that &ldquo;range throughout the whole earth.&rdquo; The concept: YHWH actively surveys the earth looking for those whose hearts are <em>šālēm</em> (whole/fully committed) — to act on their behalf. Asa himself was described as having a <em>lēḇ šālēm</em> (fully committed heart) in 15:17. Hanani is charging him with having abandoned what once defined him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s reaction: he imprisons Hanani and &ldquo;oppressed some of the people at that time.&rdquo; The imprisonment of YHWH&rsquo;s prophet is the signature act of Israelite apostasy (cf. 1 Kgs 18:4; 22:26-27; Jer 32:2-3; 37:15). The addition that Asa &ldquo;oppressed some of the people&rdquo; (<em>wayyirṣēṣ ʾāšā bāʿēt hahîʾ mĕn hāʿām</em>) is unique to Chronicles — the tyrant who silences prophets also oppresses the vulnerable. The two corruptions are linked: rejection of God&rsquo;s word correlates with injustice toward God&rsquo;s people.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The summary citation to &ldquo;the Book of the Kings of Judah and Israel.&rdquo; This bi-directional citation (Kings of Judah and Israel rather than Kings of Israel or Kings of Judah) is characteristic of Chronicles and may represent a comprehensive court annals source that covered both kingdoms. The Chronicler cites it as the repository of the full Asa narrative, indicating his account is selective.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;Even in his illness he did not seek (<em>lōʾ dāraš</em>) the LORD but turned only to physicians (<em>rōpĕʾîm</em>).&rdquo; This is the most damning verse in Asa&rsquo;s account — and the most carefully constructed. The verb <em>dāraš</em>, which appeared 8+ times in chapters 14-15 as the mark of Asa&rsquo;s faithfulness, appears here in its final negation: <em>lōʾ dāraš</em>. He refused to seek YHWH even in extremity. The physicians (<em>rōpĕʾîm</em>) are not condemned in themselves; the issue is seeking them exclusively while not seeking YHWH — the same structural failure as the Syrian treaty. MKT renders this plainly without softening the critique.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Asa&rsquo;s death in his forty-first year and his burial in the city of David concludes his account. The Chronicler records the death with the standard formula, neither condemning nor vindicating beyond what the narrative has already established. The reign is long (41 years) — the longest of any Judahite king until Manasseh (55 years) — and its arc is the great Chronicler study of faith that flourishes, then fails.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The elaborate burial — a prepared tomb, a bed of spices, a great fire in his honor — reflects the honor given to significant Judahite kings. The spice-perfumed burial bed and the honor-fire are signs of respect from the community regardless of the king&rsquo;s failures. The Chronicler does not exploit the burial account to score theological points; he records the honor the community gave to a king whose life contained both remarkable faithfulness and significant failure.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Jehoshaphat becomes king and &ldquo;consolidated his position against Israel.&rdquo; The verb <em>ḥāzaq</em> (strengthened himself/consolidated) is the standard term for a new king&rsquo;s establishment of his rule (cf. 2 Chr 12:13; 13:21; 21:4). The qualifier &ldquo;against Israel&rdquo; (<em>ʿal Yiśrāʾēl</em>) indicates the geopolitical situation: Jehoshaphat inherits the Asa-era tensions with the northern kingdom.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The military dispositions — troops in Judah&rsquo;s fortified cities and garrisons in Ephraimite towns his father captured — continue Asa&rsquo;s defensive organization (cf. 2 Chr 14:6-7; 15:8). The mention of towns captured from Ephraim places Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s defensive perimeter north of Jerusalem in former Ephraimite territory — a strategic buffer zone maintained from Asa&rsquo;s campaigns.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD was with Jehoshaphat because he followed the earlier example of his ancestor David (<em>bĕdarkê Dāwid ʾāḇîw hāriʾšōnōt</em>) and did not seek the Baals.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;the earlier example of David&rdquo; (<em>darkê hāriʾšōnōt</em> — &ldquo;the early ways&rdquo;) likely refers to David&rsquo;s undivided devotion before the Bathsheba incident — David as the covenant archetype rather than the historically complete figure. MKT renders <em>derek</em> (way/path) as &ldquo;example&rdquo; in this context, as the reference is to a pattern of life rather than a specific path.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;He sought the God of his father (<em>dāraš lēʾlōhê ʾāḇîw</em>) and followed his commands, not the practices of Israel.&rdquo; The verb <em>dāraš</em> (seek) opens Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s narrative as it opened Asa&rsquo;s — the seeking/not-seeking vocabulary is immediately established. &ldquo;The God of his father&rdquo; (<em>ʾĕlōhê ʾāḇîw</em>) emphasizes covenant continuity: Jehoshaphat inherits not just the throne but the covenant relationship. &ldquo;The practices of Israel&rdquo; (<em>maʿăśê Yiśrāʾēl</em>) refers to the Jeroboam-system of northern cult-practice.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD therefore established his rule firmly (<em>wayyikkōn YHWH ʾet hammamlākâ bĕyādô</em>).&rdquo; The divine passive of kingship establishment appears at the beginning of Solomon&rsquo;s reign (1 Chr 17:14) and Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s. The theological point: the king does not establish his own rule; YHWH does it through his covenant faithfulness. All Judah bringing tribute and Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s great riches and honor are the material expression of YHWH&rsquo;s blessing of the seeking king.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;His heart was devoted to (<em>wayyigbaH libbô</em>) the LORD&rsquo;s ways.&rdquo; The idiom <em>gābaH lēḇ</em> (heart was high/elevated) is elsewhere used negatively for pride (2 Chr 26:16; 32:25); here it is positive — his heart was lifted up toward YHWH&rsquo;s ways. This may be intentional irony: the same elevated-heart idiom that marks later kings&rsquo; pride marks Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s devotion, distinguishing its object. He removes high places and Asherah poles — extending Asa&rsquo;s reform program.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In his third year, Jehoshaphat sends officials to teach in Judah&rsquo;s towns — an unprecedented initiative. The names of the five officials (<em>śārîm</em>) are listed: Ben-hail, Obadiah, Zechariah, Nethanel, and Micaiah. The use of royal officials as teachers alongside Levites and priests is remarkable — it integrates civil and religious authority in a single educational mission, a distinctively Jehoshaphat innovation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Nine Levites and two priests are named as the teachers: Shemaiah, Nethaniah, Zebadiah, Asahel, Shemiramoth, Jehonathan, Adonijah, Tobijah, Tob-adonijah (Levites); Elishama and Jehoram (priests). The list is long and specific — the Chronicler found it worth preserving. The inclusion of both Levites and Aaronic priests in the teaching mission reflects Deuteronomy&rsquo;s vision of the priests-Levites as the custodians and teachers of the Torah (Deut 17:9-11; 31:9-13; 33:10).</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;They taught throughout Judah, taking with them the Book of the Law of the LORD (<em>sēper tôrat YHWH</em>). They traveled to every town in Judah and instructed the people.&rdquo; The phrase <em>sēper tôrat YHWH</em> (Book of the Law of the LORD) is a reference to the Mosaic Torah — the same phrase used for the book found in the temple under Josiah (2 Kgs 22:8, 11). Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s teaching mission is the most explicit example of Deuteronomy 17:18-20 (the king shall write and read the Torah) and 31:10-13 (Torah read publicly every seven years) being implemented in the monarchy.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;The terror of the LORD (<em>paḥad YHWH</em>) came upon all the surrounding kingdoms so that they did not make war against Jehoshaphat.&rdquo; The same divine terror-weapon that protected Judah in Asa&rsquo;s Cushite campaign (14:14) now operates preemptively in Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s reign. The connection between Torah-teaching (v9) and divine protection (v10) is structural in the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology — obedience to the covenant law brings covenant protection from foreign threats (Deut 28:1-14).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Philistines bring gifts and silver as tribute; Arabs bring flocks of rams and male goats. The voluntary tribute-bearing by non-Israelite peoples is a covenant-blessing sign (Deut 28:10-12; Isa 60:5-7; cf. Solomon&rsquo;s universal tribute in 2 Chr 9:23-24). The specific animals — rams and male goats — are the standard sacrificial animals, suggesting the tribute may also have included cult gifts. The specific number &ldquo;seven thousand seven hundred&rdquo; each appears precise rather than hyperbolic.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehoshaphat &ldquo;continued to grow in power (<em>wayyigdal Yĕhôšāp̄āṭ ʿad lĕmaʿlâ</em>).&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;grew to great heights&rdquo; (literally &ldquo;grew to an upward extent&rdquo;) is unique to Chronicles for a king&rsquo;s increase. The building of fortresses and supply cities throughout Judah is the infrastructure of a secure and prosperous kingdom — the material consequence of covenant faithfulness made visible in national stability.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Large stores in Judah&rsquo;s cities and fighting men stationed in Jerusalem. The combination of material stockpiles (<em>mĕlāʾkâ rabbâ</em> — &ldquo;great stores/works&rdquo;) and military readiness reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent picture of a well-ordered covenant kingdom: neither military capability nor material provision is despised, but both are understood as covenant blessings, not achievements of human strategy alone.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The military muster by ancestral divisions from Judah: Adnah with 300,000. The detail &ldquo;by their ancestral divisions&rdquo; (<em>lĕbêt ʾăḇôtām</em>) reflects the tribal-genealogical organization of Chronicles&rsquo; whole project — from the genealogies of 1 Chr 1-9 to the military lists here, the covenant community is structured by lineage. The commanders&rsquo; names are historically specific; the Chronicler had access to military records unavailable to us.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jehohanan with 280,000 — the second Judahite contingent. As a translation note: the commander names in vv14-18 are theophoric (containing divine name elements — <em>Yah-</em>, <em>-el</em>): Adnah (&ldquo;pleasure/resting&rdquo; — not theophoric), Jehohanan (&ldquo;YHWH is gracious&rdquo;), Amasiah (&ldquo;YHWH has carried&rdquo;), Eliada (&ldquo;God knows&rdquo;), Jehozabad (&ldquo;YHWH has endowed&rdquo;). The commanders&rsquo; names are themselves a catalogue of YHWH&rsquo;s attributes — grace, care, knowledge, endowment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Amasiah son of Zichri, &ldquo;who had volunteered for the LORD&rsquo;s service (<em>hammitnaddēḇ laYHWH</em>),&rdquo; with 200,000. The participle <em>mitnaddēḇ</em> (volunteer, self-devoted) carries covenantal weight — it is the term used for those who offered freely for the tabernacle (Exod 35:29; 36:3) and the temple (1 Chr 29:5-9, 14, 17). A military commander described as &ldquo;self-devoted to YHWH&rdquo; is a soldier-priest, his service of God expressed through arms.</p>",
    "17": "<p>From Benjamin: Eliada (&ldquo;God knows&rdquo;) with 200,000 archers and shield-bearers. Benjamin&rsquo;s archery tradition (cf. Judg 20:16; 1 Chr 8:40; 12:2) continues under Jehoshaphat. The tribal specialization persists through generations — Benjaminite archers were a recognized military asset in Israel&rsquo;s armies from the period of the judges onward.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehozabad (&ldquo;YHWH has endowed&rdquo;) with 180,000 equipped for war — the last Benjaminite contingent. The grand total across all five contingents: 300,000 + 280,000 + 200,000 (Judah) + 200,000 + 180,000 (Benjamin) = 1,160,000 fighting men. The number is again in the hyperbolic register; its theological function is to convey the scale of YHWH&rsquo;s blessing on the seeking king — a covenant army of extraordinary size as the fruit of Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s Torah-centered faithfulness.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The concluding note: &ldquo;These served the king, in addition to those he had stationed in the fortified cities throughout Judah.&rdquo; The chapter ends on a picture of comprehensive military security — garrisons, field armies, supplies — all flowing from the king&rsquo;s seeking of God and the people&rsquo;s instruction in the Torah. The Chronicler&rsquo;s vision of the well-ordered covenant kingdom: teaching the Torah (v9), receiving divine protection (v10), attracting tribute (v11), and fielding a powerful army (vv14-18) are not separate blessings but one integrated flourishing.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-original', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRON2)
    save_comm('mkt-original', '2chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRON2.values())
    print(f'2chronicles mkt-original: wrote {count} verses for ch 13-17')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
